<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1683,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1719,1745]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Remarks.</emphasis>
The two species are very similar in general morphology, size and colouration in both males and females. Only the female subgenital plate and male tenth abdominal tergite show clear-cut species differences (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). The female tenth abdominal tergite and epiproct did not exhibit species differences (
<figureCitation box="[1131,1200,1791,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-254@5.[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Monseremus appendiculatus (A, B) and Monseremus bellus (C, D): female abdominal apex in posterior view (A, C); female stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B, D). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825667/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1683,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">
The number of pegs on the two stridulatory files on each of the second and third tergites can be variable within species (second tergite 
<specimenCount box="[422,444,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[444,459,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
4–6, 
<specimenCount box="[524,546,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[546,561,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
12–14; third tergite 
<specimenCount box="[800,820,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
12–14 and 
<specimenCount box="[953,968,1863,1890]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
15–17, 
<specimenCount box="[1061,1082,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[1083,1098,1863,1889]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<quantity box="[1098,1206,1863,1889]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.445" metricValueMax="4.826" metricValueMin="4.064" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" unit="in" value="17.5" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="16.0">16–19 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tan &amp; Japir &amp; Chung &amp; Robillard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Tan &amp; Wahab" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[1217,1436,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1217,1436,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Monseremus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,282,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,282,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
[n = 
<specimenCount box="[350,387,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">4♂</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount box="[402,437,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">4♀</specimenCount>
]) and do not appear show clear species differences (
<emphasis box="[1048,1079,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">vs.</emphasis>
<specimenCount box="[1088,1110,1899,1926]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[1110,1125,1899,1926]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
4–5, 
<specimenCount box="[1189,1211,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[1211,1227,1899,1925]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
11–13; 
<specimenCount box="[1317,1339,1899,1926]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[1339,1354,1899,1926]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
15–17, 
<specimenCount box="[151,172,1935,1961]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
<specimenCount box="[173,188,1935,1961]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<quantity box="[188,294,1935,1961]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.318" metricValueMax="4.572" metricValueMin="4.064" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" unit="in" value="17.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="16.0">16–18 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[302,623,1935,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[302,623,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Monseremus appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[n = 
<specimenCount box="[688,725,1935,1961]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="male">2♂</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount box="[738,773,1935,1961]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="female">2♀</specimenCount>
]) (
<figureCitation box="[808,878,1935,1961]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-254@5.[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Monseremus appendiculatus (A, B) and Monseremus bellus (C, D): female abdominal apex in posterior view (A, C); female stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B, D). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825667/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Likewise, the shape of the stridulatory files are also not different between the two species (
<figureCitation box="[636,705,1971,1997]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-254@5.[151,1436,936,1898]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Monseremus appendiculatus (A, B) and Monseremus bellus (C, D): female abdominal apex in posterior view (A, C); female stridulatory files on second and third tergites (B, D). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825667/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Hence, these characters are unlikely to be important for species diagnosis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[151,419,151,177]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="multiple">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,419,151,177]" box="[151,419,151,177]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,419,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,419,151,177]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Key to known species</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="109" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<key pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,220,447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
1. Female: projections at the anterior margin of the subgenital plate larger, more bulbous (in lateral view), and longer in length than subgenital plate (
<figureCitation box="[435,554,249,271]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Figs 2A, 2B</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor longer, length&gt;17.0 mm. Male: medial processes of the tenth abdominal tergite with inner margins and apices clearly separated (
<figureCitation box="[692,768,279,301]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate faintly more squarish, ca. 1.7 times wider than long (
<figureCitation box="[233,309,308,330]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Distribution: highland forests in 
<collectingRegion box="[639,700,308,330]" country="Malaysia" name="Sabah" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Sabah</collectingRegion>
, East 
<collectingCountry box="[757,848,308,330]" name="Malaysia" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
.......................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[1162,1437,308,330]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculatus">
<emphasis box="[1162,1437,308,330]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Monseremus appendiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,220,447]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
-. Female: projections at the anterior margin of the subgenital plate smaller, more flattened (in lateral view), and shorter in length than subgenital plate (
<figureCitation box="[437,544,367,389]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Figs 2D, E</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor shorter, length &lt;
<quantity box="[826,914,367,389]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" unit="mm" value="16.5">16.5 mm</quantity>
. Male: medial processes of the tenth abdominal tergite with inner margins and apices touching each other (
<figureCitation box="[730,805,396,418]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate more transverse, ca. 2.5 times wider than long (
<figureCitation box="[233,307,425,447]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Monseremus appendiculatus (A–C) and Monseremus bellus (D–F): female subgenital plate in ventral (A, D) and lateral (B, E) views; male abdominal apex in ventral view (C, F). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6825659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6825659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
). Distribution: lowland forests in 
<collectingCountry box="[630,820,425,447]" name="Brunei" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Brunei Darussalam</collectingCountry>
..................................... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tan &amp; Japir &amp; Chung &amp; Robillard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Tan &amp; Wahab" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[1251,1436,425,447]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Monseremus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis box="[1251,1436,425,447]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Monseremus bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</key>
